Potassium ferrate. A name that probably doesn't set anyone's heart racing, but here we are. It’s an [inorganic compound](/Inorganic_compound) – specifically, a [salt](/Salt_(chemistry)) – bearing the rather precise [formula](/Chemical_formula) [K 2 FeO 4](/Chemical_formula). For those who appreciate such distinctions, it is the potassium salt of what is known as [ferric acid](/Ferric_acid). In the grand scheme of chemical agents, [potassium ferrate](/Potassium_ferrate) distinguishes itself as a potent [oxidizing agent](/Oxidizing_agent). Its utility spans various domains, from its more noble applications in [green chemistry](/Green_chemistry) and [water treatment](/Water_treatment), to the intricate dance of [organic synthesis](/Organic_synthesis), and even the more cutting-edge realm of [cathode technology](/Cathode). A true multitasker, if one were inclined to give it such a compliment.

### Names

The nomenclature of chemical compounds, a tedious necessity, provides us with the following designations for this particular substance.

*   **[IUPAC name](/Chemical_nomenclature)**: Potassium ferrate(VI)
    *   The "(VI)" here is not a roman numeral indicating its age or prestige, but rather the [oxidation state](/Oxidation_state) of the [iron](/Iron) atom within the [ferrate ion](/Ferrate). This hexavalent state is what grants it its formidable oxidizing power, a detail often overlooked by those who simply glance at a label.
*   **Other names**:
    *   Potassium ferrate
    *   Dipotassium ferrate
    *   These are merely less formal, yet equally descriptive, ways of referring to the same entity, emphasizing the two [potassium ions](/Potassium) present.

